Scotland's independent schools are still distinguished by academic excellence. This has continued in 2018 with further outstanding examination results and is only underpinned by individual and joint successes in the fields of sports, art, music and other community activities.
With more than 30,000 students from all over Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to care for their pupils and their parents at the highest possible level.
Independent schools pursue the goal of preparing their pupils for further education and higher education, the profession of their choice and their place as a world citizen.
As an educational sector that can design and implement a tailor-made curriculum, we see that modern languages are still popular and desirable in schools.
Nelson Mandela said: “If you talk to someone in a language he understands, you reach his head.
If you speak to him in his own language, you will reach his heart."
This is an impressive reminder that we cannot rely only on English if we want to build relations and trust with people from other countries.
The current audit results of this year we find that languages with the highest existing rates are at the top of the rankings of independent schools.
A total of 68 percent of students who learned foreign languages achieved Note A during the higher examinations.
From the data collected by 74 SCIS member schools, 72 percent of the students in Mandarin achieved Note A during the higher examinations, while 72 percent of the students who learned German, 69 percent of the students who learned French, and 63 percent of the students who learned Spanish also achieved Note A.
