A new course at Harvard University ensures that all students get more sleep in basic education this year. This is an action against the spreading macho culture, keeping themselves awake with caffeine and learning all night long.
One scientist has found that students at the world's leading university are often unneeded when it comes to paying attention.
The course was conceived by Charles Czeisler, professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital and is in his opinion the first such course in the United States.
He was inspired to start the course after giving a lecture on the effects of sleep deprivation on learning.
“At the end, a girl came to me and asked, ‘Why am I only experiencing this now, in my last year?’
