This year's first course explained how the basics of good sleep habits contribute to academic and sporting performance and also improve general well-being.
Paul Barreira, Professor of Psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and Managing Director of Health Services at the University, said that the university had opted for the introduction of the course after she had found that students were suffering from severe sleep deprivation during the week.
The one-hour course includes a series of interactive tasks.
In a section the students see the picture of a room in a living room and click on coffee cups, curtains, training shoes and books. They receive information about the effect of caffeine and light as well as the effects of lack of sleep on the sporty performance and the importance of a sleeping routine.
In another section, participants learn that long-term sleep withdrawal can increase the risk of heart attacks, strokes and cancer.
They are then encouraged to think about their daily routine using an interactive map of the university site.
“We know that it will not change the behavior of the students immediately.
But we believe that they have the right to know this – just as you have the right to know how the decision to smoke affects your health," added Professor Czeisler.
The pride of pushing a "night shift" was still widespread, he said and added that modern technologies and the ever-increasing pressure on students made sleep deprivation a growing problem.
Sufficiently good sleep, the "secret weapon" of all students should be against stress, exhaustion and anxiety, he said. Furthermore, weight gain was avoided, as sleep deprivation put the brain in starvation mode so that they were constantly hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old student from California who studies chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler to design the course. He had won one of his courses last year in Harvard.
