The Global Citizens Festival, which took place for the first time in 2012, is an extension of the Global Poverty Project. As part of this project, an international interest group tries to fight poverty by motivating more and more people to participate actively in the fight against poverty.
In order to obtain a free ticket for the event (the other option would be to buy a VIP ticket), you need to do a number of tasks. These include actions such as volunteering, communication with a leading politician worldwide (by e-mail or telephone) or similar measures to raise awareness of the goal of fighting poverty.
How successful is the project, considering that Global Citizen will remain 12 years to achieve the goal?
Is it the idea to put a cool free concert in perspective, a useful way to convince others that it is time to act, or just another case of so-called clicktivism – if you think you can change something by signing an online petition or sending a tweet?
Global Citizen reported that since 2011, the project has been able to record more than 19 million actions from its supporters and achieve different goals.
These actions should have helped to encourage leading politicians around the world to announce commitments and strategies worth more than $37 billion, which will affect the lives of more than 2.25 billion people by 2030.
At the beginning of 2018, the Group cited 390 commitments and announcements arising from its actions, at least USD 10 billion of which have already been paid out or contracted by fundraising.
According to group estimates, the funds secured to date have a direct impact on almost 649 million people around the world.
Some of the most important obligations are the project The Power of Nutrition, a partnership of investors and implementers based in the United Kingdom who have committed themselves to support children in their optimal development, and who have promised to help Rwanda with USD 35 million to fight malnutrition in the country after receiving more than 4,700 tweets from Global Citizens.
"With the support of the United Kingdom Government, donors, national governments and global citizens like you, we can make the social injustice of malnutrition a footnote in history," the Ambassador of The Power of Nutrition, Tracey Ullman, announced to the audience during a live concert in London in April 2018.
The Group also announced that, after more than 5,000 actions involving the UK were called upon to improve the nutritional situation of mothers and children, the government announced the financing of the The Power of Nutrition project, which aims to reach 5 million women and children and provides food interventions.
In response to one of the frequently asked questions on the website, namely the question, what are the reasons why Global Citizens can fight extreme poverty,
they replied: “It will be a long and strenuous path with heights and depths.
But like the big civil rights and anti-apartheid movements in front of us, we will have success, as we are stronger and more influential together.
