In an estate in the Scottish Highlands, new research will be carried out to show how bats use the landscape in food search.
It is hoped that the results will enable further insights into the behaviour of these unique flying mammals and help to initiate future nature conservation activities.
The study carried out by researchers at the National Trust for Scotland will detect dwarf and mosquito bats as well as the brown Langohr and water bats in Inverewe Garden in West Ross.
Special recording devices are placed at key positions on the plot to record bat activities throughout the season.
Employees of the NHS and volunteers will also conduct mobile studies with portable detectors.
When analysing all recordings by experts, the frequency of bat calls is determined and what species does.
A map and a report of the habitat will then be created to create a detailed picture of their behaviour at landscape level.
Rob Dewar, conservation consultant for the NTS, hopes that the results will show which areas of the habitat are most important for bats and how these are used by each species.
These data will help to determine the benefits of measures to manage the habitat, such as the creation of meadows, and to show how to preserve forest areas for bats and other related species.
The bat stocks in Scotland and the whole of the United Kingdom have declined significantly in the last century.
They are threatened by construction and development, which have an impact on sleeping places and lead to the loss of living space.
Windwheels and lighting can also pose a risk, as can fly-flying and the chemical treatment of building materials or also attacks by house cats.
Bats are not really blind.
