They use a sophisticated echotype to detect insects and obstacles in their flight path.
The NTS, responsible for the care of over 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land throughout Scotland, takes the theme of bats very seriously.
He has 10 trained experts who regularly carry out examinations, inspections of sleeping places and sometimes rescue measures.
The organization has even established Scotland's first and only bat reserve in the Threave estate in Dumfries and Galloway, which is home to eight of Scotland's 10 bat species.
Guts manager David Thompson explains that the property is the ideal habitat for them.
"Here in Threeave we have a great area for bats," he explains.
“We have the old buildings, many old trees and an excellent habitat.
But there are many things we do not yet know about bats, so here and on other goods we carry out these works that will help us learn more about what bats need to feel comfortable."
He emphasises the importance of excluding the presence of bats before maintenance work in the goods, since it is possible that the accidental destruction of a single nest site could kill up to 400 females and young animals and the entire population on the spot.
Bats are under protection and it is illegal to kill them, to harass them or to destroy them or their nest sites.
Elisabeth Ferrell, Scottish wife of the Bat Conservation Trust, encouraged the population to help.
