The opening ointments of the trade war between the US and China were deafening. Although the battle is not over for a long time, Beijing could benefit from a long-term digging between the countries, my experts.
Donald Trump, U.S. president, fired the first warning at the beginning of the year when he used criminal tariffs to carry out important Chinese export goods, including solar cells, steel and aluminium.
The most significant escalation took place this week with new criminal tariffs on goods worth 200 billion dollars, effectively affecting half of all goods imported from China into the USA.
Every time Beijing struck back in the same way, and recently, it imposed fines of five to ten percent on American goods worth 60 billion dollars.
China vowed to respond to any US action and it is unlikely that the second largest economic power in the world will soon stumble.
Moving Washington to slow down would mean giving in. However, a public knock on the United States would be far too flattering for China’s President Xi Jinping.
Nevertheless, experts believe that if Beijing plays out its cards well, China can benefit from the effects of the trade war in the long term by reducing the interdependence of the two economies.
"The fact that a rapid political decision could either create the conditions for economic turbulence in both countries in Washington or Beijing is actually much more dangerous than many observers have known before," says Abigail Grace, a scientific assistant who focuses on Asia at the Center for New American Security.
Syria was 'ready' for the return of refugees, according to the Minister for Foreign Affairs
Syria says it is ready for the voluntary return of refugees and asks for help for the reconstruction of the country devastated by the war lasting for more than seven years.
In a speech before the United Nations General Assembly, Foreign Minister Walid al-Moualem stated that the circumstances in the country are improving.
"Today, thanks to the progress made in the fight against terrorism, the situation on the ground is more stable and safer," he said.
The government is rebuilding the areas destroyed by terrorists to reverse normality.
All conditions were now in place for the voluntary return of refugees to the country, which they had to leave because of terrorism and unilateral economic measures that had their daily lives and livelihoods.
The UN estimates that more than 5.5 million Syrians have left the country since the beginning of the war in 2011.
Another six million people still living in the country are in need of humanitarian aid.
Al-Moualem said that the Syrian government welcomes assistance in rebuilding the devastated country.
However, he stressed that it would not accept conditional assistance from countries that had supported the uprising.
Europe won the Ryder Cup in Paris
Team Europe won the Ryder Cup 2018 and defeated Team USA at the Le Golf National near Paris with a final score of 16.5 to 10.5.
The United States has now lost six consecutive times on European soil and has not won a Ryder Cup in Europe since 1993.
Europe regained the crown after the team of Danish captain Thomas Bjorn reached the 14.5 points it needed to defeat the US.
The American star Phil Mickelson, who had problems with most of the tournament, sank his exit on the 16th track (Par 3) in the water and lost to Francesco Molinari.
The Italian golfer Molinari was able to shine in all its rounds and became one of 4 players who scored a 5-0-0 since the tournament began in its current format in 1979.
The American Jordan Spieth was hit 5:4 by the player with the lowest ranking in the team Europe, Thorbjorn Olesen from Denmark.
The player with the world's best ranking, Dustin Johnson, lost 2 to 1 against the Englishman Ian Poulter, who may have played his last Ryder Cup.
The Spaniard Sergio Garcia, veteran from eight Ryder Cups, became the best European Ryder Cup player ever with 25.5 career points.
“Normally I don’t cry, but today I couldn’t hold back.
It was a difficult year.
I am so grateful that Thomas chose me and believed in me.
I'm so infinitely happy to win the Cup back.
It's about the team and I'm happy to have made a contribution," says emotional Garcia after the European victory.
He passed on the torch to his compatriot John Rahm, who won the solo encounters against the American golf legend Tiger Woods on Sunday 2:1.
I'm so incredibly proud to have beaten Tiger Woods I've been watching since my childhood on television," says 23-year-old Ram.
Woods lost all his four games in France and now has a Ryder Cup balance of 13-21-3.
A strange statistic for one of the biggest players of all time who won 14 important titles and is surpassed only by Jack Nicklaus.
The team USA had all weekend problems to find the fairways, with the exception of Patrick Reed, Justin Thomas and Tony Finau, who performed high-quality performances throughout the tournament.
American captain Jim Fury said after a disappointing performance of his team: “I am proud of the boys, they have fought.
There was a time this morning when we put Europe under pressure.
We didn't do anything about it.
Take off for Thomas.
He's a great captain.
All of his 12 players performed well.
We'll regroup, I'll talk to the PGA America and our Ryder Cup committee and we'll look forward.
I love those 12 guys and I'm proud to be their captain.
You have to pull the hat.
We were defeated."
Red Time Update: Concentrations in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota decrease
The latest report by the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission shows that a general decrease in red tide concentrations is recorded in parts of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the FWC, in the areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier, there are gaps in flowering conditions, indicating declining concentrations.
A red algae flower extends over about 130 miles of coastline from the northern Pinellas to the south of the district of Lee.
Few spots can be found about 10 miles off the Hillsborough coast, but compared to the previous week in fewer places.
A red tide was also observed in the district of Pasco.
Last week, mid-term concentrations on or off the Pinellas coast were reported, low to high concentrations off the coast of Manatee District, background to high concentrations on or off the Charlotte District Coast, background to high concentrations on or off Lee District Coast and low concentrations in Collier District.
Respiratory complaints are still reported from the districts of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier.
In the northwest of Florida, no new respiratory problems have been reported over the last week.
